[[File:DuquesneBreweryBuilding1899.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The old [[Duquesne Brewing Company]] building, built in 1899, is the home of the Brew House Association.]] '''The Brew House Association''' is an [[artist collective]] established in 1991 in the [[South Side Flats]] neighborhood of [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]. It is located at Mary and 21st Streets in a multi-story building that once housed the [[Duquesne Brewing Company]]. The lower floors of the building have been converted to gallery and theater space, including SPACE 101, an alternative exhibit gallery founded by the Brew House Association in 1994, while the upper floors have become studio and living areas for resident artists, and shared workshops for [[welding]] and [[pottery]]. The Brew House and the abandoned industrial lots around it have been the site of [[performance art]], [[theatre]] and [[sculpture]] exhibits. They formerly rented studio space and hosted a residency program for [[visual artist]]s before issues with building code violations forced them to temporarily close their doors in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Brew House Association|url=http://pittsburgharts.org/brew-house-association-call-proposals-2013|publisher=Pittsburgh Arts|quote=The Brew House Association operates within the original Duquesne Brewing facility founded in 1899.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020075612/http://pittsburgharts.org/brew-house-association-call-proposals-2013|archivedate=2014-10-20|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tim Schooley|title=South Side Brew House to be renovated into 75 apartments|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/news/2014/03/03/south-side-brew-house-to-be-renovated.html|publisher=Pittsburgh Business Times|date=March 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Charles Rosenblum|title=Brew House artists are renovating their South Side home, but not changing their mission|url=http://www.pghcitypaper.com/pittsburgh/brew-house-artists-are-renovating-their-south-side-home-but-not-changing-their-mission/Content?oid=1736019|publisher=Pittsburgh City Paper|date=March 12, 2014}}</ref>
